    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:be18cd80-8524-4c58-9b9a-d8d1e89e66da",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 10-year-old boy who appears his stated age, small for his class but well nourished, usually arriving with his mother and clutching a worn backpack with a few toy cars inside. He is alert and cooperative between episodes, though somewhat shy at first and prone to glancing toward his parent for reassurance. Over the last year, his family has noticed intermittent events in which he abruptly stops what he is doing, stares blankly, and becomes unresponsive for several seconds; on two occasions he has had a generalized convulsive episode with rhythmic jerking followed by confusion and exhaustion. He often complains of feeling tired afterward and sometimes has a mild headache.\n\nHe is a fourth-grade student who enjoys soccer, drawing dinosaurs, and playing age-appropriate video games with friends from school. His teachers describe him as bright but increasingly distracted, largely because of missed class time and brief unexplained staring spells. He lives with both parents and a younger sister in a suburban home. The family is attentive and highly involved, and they have begun making practical safety adjustments such as supervised bathing, helmet use for biking, and closer observation during sports.\n\nHis daily routine is otherwise typical for his age. He eats a mixed diet, prefers pasta and fruit, and has no exposure to tobacco, alcohol, or drugs. Sleep has recently become irregular because his parents are anxious about nocturnal events, and occasional sleep deprivation seems to make his episodes more likely. There is no suggestion of neglect or poor social support; instead, the household is stable, caring, and focused on helping {patientName} remain active and independent while staying safe.\n\nOn examination days, he may appear mildly fatigued, especially after a recent seizure, but he generally has a normal gait, age-appropriate speech, and no obvious focal neurologic deficit. He can become embarrassed when discussing seizures in front of peers and worries about being treated differently at school. His parents report that emotional stress, missed sleep, and febrile illness may increase the likelihood of events, though a clear consistent trigger has not always been identified."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:b4247744-185b-414e-929f-381176713316",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has had recurrent unprovoked seizure-like episodes for approximately 8 months. The first events were described as brief staring spells occurring several times per week, each lasting 5 to 15 seconds, with abrupt return to baseline. Two months ago, he had a witnessed generalized convulsive seizure at home lasting about 2 minutes, followed by 20 to 30 minutes of postictal confusion and somnolence. A second similar event occurred during an upper respiratory infection. There is no known history of major head trauma, central nervous system infection, developmental regression, or toxic ingestion.\n\nPast medical history is notable for mild intermittent asthma and seasonal allergic rhinitis. Immunizations are current. He has never been hospitalized long term, though he was evaluated in the emergency department after the first convulsive seizure and discharged after stabilization and outpatient neurology referral. Birth history was uncomplicated, and developmental milestones were achieved on time. School performance has been average to good, though recent concentration concerns are thought to be related to seizure burden.\n\nLifestyle factors relevant to his seizure history include inconsistent sleep on weekends and high excitement during evening screen time. He does not use caffeine regularly beyond occasional soda. Safety counseling has already been discussed with the family, including supervision around water, avoiding heights without protection, and informing school staff about seizure first aid."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
